So, that - finally - brings an end to Australia's innings after some grinding resistance from their lower order. Paine and Hilfenhaus put on 74 for the ninth wicket before these two added a further 52. Australia are totally in charge of this game now, Pakistan will need 440 to win this game, and there's a session and two days for Australia to chip away. The players wander off towards the pavilion for the tea interval.

Pakistan will need to set a new world record if they are to win this game, beating the previous record chase of 418 for 7 by West Indies against Australia at the ARG in Antigua. The highest fourth innings chase at Lord's is 344 for 1, by West Indies in 1984. Pakistan's highest winning fourth innings total is 315 for 9, against Australia in Karachi in 1994. So history is not exactly on their side.

In the other international match being played today, Bangladesh are being given a tough time by Ireland's openers at Stormont, and something of an upset is on the cards!

There's also Andrew Miller's teatime bulletin to enjoy.
